ğŸ” Step 3: Create OIDC Identity Provider (AWS Console)
	1. Go to IAM Console
	2. Click Identity providers â†’ Add provider
	3. Choose OpenID Connect
	4. Enter: 
		â—‹ Provider URL: https://token.actions.githubusercontent.com
		â—‹ Audience: sts.amazonaws.com
	5. Click Get thumbprint â†’ then Add provider

ğŸ›¡ï¸ Step 4: Create IAM Role for GitHub OIDC
	1. Go to IAM â†’ Roles â†’ Create Role
	2. Choose Web Identity â†’ Select the OIDC provider you created
	3. Set Audience to sts.amazonaws.com
	4. Attach policies: 
		â—‹ AmazonEKSClusterPolicy
		â—‹ AmazonEKSServicePolicy
		â—‹ AmazonEC2ContainerRegistryReadOnly
	5. Name the role: GitHubActionsEKSRole
	6. Create the role
ğŸ“ Edit Trust Policy:
Go to the role â†’ Trust relationships â†’ Edit trust policy 
Paste this (replace placeholders):
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [{
    "Effect": "Allow",
    "Principal": {
      "Federated": "arn:aws:iam::<YOUR_ACCOUNT_ID>:oidc-provider/token.actions.githubusercontent.com"
    },
    "Action": "sts:AssumeRoleWithWebIdentity",
    "Condition": {
      "StringEquals": {
        "token.actions.githubusercontent.com:aud": "sts.amazonaws.com"
      },
      "StringLike": {
        "token.actions.githubusercontent.com:sub": "repo:<your-org>/<your-repo>:*"
      }
    }
  }]
}

ğŸ”‘ Step 5: Add Role ARN as GitHub Secret
	1. Go to your GitHub repo â†’ Settings â†’ Secrets â†’ Actions
	2. Add new secret: 
		â—‹ Name: AWS_ROLE_ARN
		â—‹ Value: IAM Role ARN from previous step

âš™ï¸ Step 6: Create GitHub Actions Workflow
Create .github/workflows/k8s-ops.yml in your repo:
name: EKS Kubectl Ops
on:
  workflow_dispatch:
permissions:
  id-token: write
  contents: read
jobs:
  kubectl-ops:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - name: Checkout
        uses: actions/checkout@v3
- name: Configure AWS Credentials
        uses: aws-actions/configure-aws-credentials@v4
        with:
          role-to-assume: ${{ secrets.AWS_ROLE_ARN }}
          aws-region: ap-south-1
- name: Update kubeconfig
        run: aws eks update-kubeconfig --region ap-south-1 --name dev-cluster
- name: Run kubectl commands
        run: |
          kubectl get pods -A
          kubectl get secrets -A

ğŸš€ Step 7: Trigger the Workflow
	â€¢ Go to Actions tab in GitHub
	â€¢ Select EKS Kubectl Ops
	â€¢ Click Run workflow
Youâ€™ll see kubectl outputs directly in the logs!

